Good — now let’s go deeper like a real SRE debugging in production.
Think of this problem in layers, not random guessing.

🧠 Mental Model (VERY IMPORTANT)
When changes are not reflecting, break the system into 5 layers:

CI/CD → Image → Kubernetes → Network → Client
You debug top → down OR bottom → up, not randomly.

🔍 Step-by-Step Deep Debugging Flow
1️⃣ CI/CD Layer (Was the correct code deployed?)
Even if pipeline is ✅ success, ask:

Did it build the latest code?

Did it push a new image?

Check:
Build logs → commit ID

Docker image tag

👉 Common issue:

Pipeline succeeded but reused old artifact

Pro Tip:
Always tag image like:

app:v1.2.3 or app:<commit-id>
2️⃣ Docker/Image Layer (Is K8s using the new image?)
This is #1 root cause in real projects

Problem:
You used:

image: my-app:latest
Kubernetes says:

"I already have this image 😎" → doesn’t pull again

Check:
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
Look for:

Image: my-app:latest
Image ID: sha256:abc123
Now compare with:

docker images
Fix:
imagePullPolicy: Always
OR
Use unique tags

3️⃣ Kubernetes Layer (Did pods actually update?)
Pipeline may deploy YAML, but rollout may not happen

Check rollout status:
kubectl rollout status deployment <app>
Check replicas:
kubectl get pods -o wide
👉 Look for:

Old pod still running

New pod not created

Deep Issue:
Kubernetes only updates pods if:

Image tag changes OR

Spec changes

Force restart:
kubectl rollout restart deployment <app>
4️⃣ Application Layer (Is app serving new code?)
Sometimes pods updated, but app still old 😅

Possible causes:
App loads config from file → not refreshed

Cached data in memory

Feature flag disabled

Debug:
kubectl exec -it <pod> -- /bin/sh
Check:

Code version

Env variables

Config files

5️⃣ Service / Networking Layer
Traffic may not hit new pods.

Check:
kubectl get svc
kubectl get endpoints
👉 Ensure:

Endpoints pointing to new pods

Deep Issue:
Readiness probe failing → pod not added to service

Old pods still receiving traffic

6️⃣ Ingress / Load Balancer Layer
Very common in real production

Problems:
Ingress caching

Sticky sessions (user always routed to old pod)

Check:
Ingress logs

LB config

Fix:
Restart ingress controller

Disable caching

7️⃣ Client Layer (Most Ignored 😄)
Issues:
Browser cache

CDN cache

Test:
Incognito

Curl API directly:

curl http://service-ip
🔥 Real-World Root Causes Ranking (From Experience)
Same image tag (latest)

Pods not restarted

Wrong namespace/environment

Cache (browser/CDN)

Readiness probe issues

ConfigMap not reloaded

🧪 Example Scenario (Interview GOLD)
Pipeline succeeded, but users still see old UI.

My approach:
Check rollout → pods updated or not

Verify image tag → same or new

Describe pod → confirm image SHA

Curl service → bypass browser cache

Check ingress → routing correct or not

Restart deployment if needed

🎯 Perfect Interview Answer (Strong)
I approach this issue layer by layer. First, I verify if the correct image was built and pushed. Then I check Kubernetes rollout status and confirm whether new pods are running with the updated image. If pods are correct, I validate service routing, ingress behavior, and finally rule out caching issues at browser or CDN level.

