After CI/CD deploy

During incident debugging

👉 Output:

deployment "app" successfully rolled out
📌 2. View Rollout History
kubectl rollout history deployment <app>
🔍 Purpose:
Shows previous versions (revisions)

🧠 When to use:
To check what versions were deployed earlier

Before rollback

🔎 Detailed version:
kubectl rollout history deployment <app> --revision=2
👉 Shows:

Image used

Changes made

📌 3. Restart Deployment (MOST USED 🔥)
kubectl rollout restart deployment <app>
🔍 Purpose:
Restart pods without changing YAML

🧠 When to use:
Changes not reflecting

ConfigMap/Secret updated

Force refresh pods

📌 4. Undo / Rollback Deployment
kubectl rollout undo deployment <app>
🔍 Purpose:
Rollback to previous version

🔎 Specific version rollback:
kubectl rollout undo deployment <app> --to-revision=2
🧠 When to use:
New release is broken

Production issue after deploy

📌 5. Pause Rollout
kubectl rollout pause deployment <app>
🔍 Purpose:
Temporarily stop updates

🧠 When to use:
During controlled deployments

Debugging before full rollout

📌 6. Resume Rollout
kubectl rollout resume deployment <app>
🔍 Purpose:
Continue paused deployment

📌 7. Check Rollout Progress (Alternative way)
kubectl get deployment <app>
👉 Look at:

READY

UP-TO-DATE

AVAILABLE

📌 8. Describe Deployment (Deep Debug)
kubectl describe deployment <app>
🔍 Purpose:
Shows rollout events

Errors during deployment

🔥 Real-Time Usage Mapping
Scenario	Command
Verify deployment success	rollout status
See old versions	rollout history
App not updated	rollout restart
Bad deployment	rollout undo
Controlled release	pause / resume
Debug issue	describe deployment
🧠 Important Internal Concept (Interview Boost)
Kubernetes rollout works using:

ReplicaSets

Each update → new ReplicaSet created

Old ReplicaSet kept for rollback

🎯 Interview Answer (2–3 lines)
Kubernetes rollout commands are used to manage deployment lifecycle. I commonly use rollout status to verify deployments, restart to refresh pods, history to track revisions, and undo to rollback in case of failures. These commands help ensure controlled and reliable releases.

